    {
      "type": "grammar_spotlight",
      "content": "Look at the end of the poem above: 秋風ぞ吹く (Akikaze zo fuku). \n\n1. **The Spotlight**: By placing 'zo' after 'Akikaze' (Autumn Wind), the poet is saying: 'It is specifically the *autumn wind* (and nothing else) that is blowing.'\n2. **The Binding**: Because 'zo' is used, the verb 'fuku' (to blow) must be in the **Rentaikei**. While 'fuku' looks the same in its standard form, grammatically it has switched roles to 'close' the emphasis started by 'zo'. This 'handshake' between the particle and the ending is the essence of Kakari-Musubi.",
      "evidence": "See the poem above."
    },
